 In its judgement of 27 June 1986 in the Military and Paramilitary Activities case , the Court stipulated that it could not take the view that Nicaragua actually undertook a commitment to organize free elections , and that this commitment was of a legal nature . The Nicaraguan Junta planned the holding of free elections as part of its political programme of government ,   following   the recommendation of the Organization of American States . This was an essentially political pledge the Court can not find an instrument with legal force , whether unilateral or synallagmatic , whereby Nicaragua has committed itself .
